'''Haibat Khan Niazi''' was a Pashtun noble and military leader. He was the most powerful noble of [[Sher Shah Suri]] and Commander of the [[Niazi]] contingent of his army.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.khyber.org/tribes/info/Early_history_of_Niazi_tribe.shtml|title = Early history of Niazi tribe|date = 4 March 2015|access-date = 17 Jan 2016|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> He is best known for bringing law and order in [[Multan]] by destroying the power of Balochs and Fetah Khan Jat who were laying waste to entire South Punjab. [[Sher Shah Suri]] granted him the title of Azam Hamayun<ref>{{Cite book|title = A History of India Under the Two First Sovereigns of the House of Taimur, Báber and Humáyun, vol. 2|last = Erskine|first = William|publisher = Longman, Brown, Green, and Longmans|year = 1854|isbn = |location = Mogul Empire|pages = 455}}</ref> and appointed him governor of [[Maharashtra]].<ref name="Agrawal1983">{{cite book|first=Ashvini |last=Agrawal|title=Studies in Mughal History|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=AZdCrUxFAHEC|page=66}}|date=1 January 1983|p=66|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-2326-6}}</ref> Currently, the sub-clans of Gen. Haybat Khan Niaziresiding mainly in Isakhel;Mianwali.

== Conquest of Kashmir, Multan and Sindh ==
Sher Shah Suri ordered Khan to conquer [[Kashmir]], Multan and [[Sindh]] in present-day [[Pakistan]]. Haibat Khan first conquered [[Jammu and Kashmir|Kashmir]] and installed the Chak dynasty. The conquest of Multan and Sindh and the restoration of law and order was completed by November, 1543.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Mughal Empire in India: A Systematic Study Including Source Material, Volume 1|last = Sharma|first = S.R.|publisher = Atlantic Publishers|year = 1999|isbn = 9788171568178|location = India|pages = 127}}</ref>

